<h2 id="lessons" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Key Takeaways</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside mt-2">
  <li>Don't forget about <a href="#learned1" class="text-purple-800 dark:text-purple-200">Ludonarrative Consonance!</a></li>
  <li><a href="#learned2" class="text-purple-800 dark:text-purple-200">Align Narrative</a> with other disciplines.</li>
  <li><a href="#learned3" class="text-purple-800 dark:text-purple-200">Iterate</a> as much as possible.</li>
  <li><a href="#learned4" class="text-purple-800 dark:text-purple-200">Write LESS.</a></li>
</ol>

<h2 id="goals" class="font-semibold text-xl mt-4 mb-2">Goals</h2>
<ul class="list-disc ml-8">
    <li>Tell a story that is age appropriate for middle-schoolers, but enjoyable for all ages</li>
    <li>Create characters that have depth and chemistry</li>
    <li>Write a satisfying character arc for Az and parallel arc for Winston</li>
</ul>

{# LESSON 4 #}
<div class="mb-4 rounded-lg p-2 mt-4 border border-purple-200 dark:border-purple-800 bg-purple-100 dark:bg-purple-900/20 rounded-lg">
  <h3 id="learned1" class="font-semibold">Lesson 1: Ludonarrative Consonance</h3>
    <p class="ml-8">Ludonarrative consonance is a fancy word that basically means the gameplay and the story are closely tied together. The gameplay is acting out the story, and the story serves the gameplay.</p>
    <p class="ml-8 mt-4">Ex: an early decision we made was to remove combat from our game. This is because the main character is a 12 year old kid whose goal is to help others. Combat simply doesn't make sense with this context.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="inspiration" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Inspiration</h2>
<p>For both story and world building, we took inspiration from Deltarune and Adventure Time.<p>
<h4 class="mt-2">Deltarune:</h4>
<ul class="list-disc ml-8">
  <li>A small band of characters with a lot of depth</li>
  <li>Balancing light-hearted comedy with serious scenes</li>
</ul>
<h4 class="mt-2">Adventure Time:</h4>
<ul class="list-disc ml-8 mb-2">
  <li>World loosely inspired by Medieval Fantasy, but with modern elements</li>
  <li>A PG, light-hearted story, even villains have moments of friendship with the cast</li>
</ul>
<p>See our <a class="text-purple-700 dark:text-purple-200" href="#bible">Narrative Bible</a> for more information on our inspirations.</p>

<h2 id="in" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">How Writing Appears in Leaves of Fate</h2>
<p>We split up our game writing into four categories:</p>
<h4>Major conversations:</h4>
  <p class="ml-8">Major conversations required cutscenes that are place dthroughout the level. They guide the player on a story arc.</p> 
<h4>Filler conversations:</h4>
  <p class="ml-8">Filler conversations with NPCs are optional. They add depth to the characters, their relationships, or the world. </p>
<h4>Barks:</h4>
  <p class="ml-8">Barks are short phrases the companion NPC, Az, makes to encourage and build rapport wtih the player.</p>
<h4>Environmental comments:</h4>
  <p class="ml-8">Environmental comments are optional moments where the player character comments on something about the environement. They add depth to the player character or the world.</p>

  {# LESSON 1 #}
<div class="mb-4 rounded-lg p-2 mt-4 border border-purple-200 dark:border-purple-800 bg-purple-100 dark:bg-purple-900/20 rounded-lg">
  <h3 id="learned2" class="font-semibold">Lesson 2: Align Narrative</h3>
    <p class="ml-8">Condensed production timeframe and limited art capacity forced our narrative to be flexible. Some story beats weren’t possible because we didn’t have proper art, tech, or otherwise. While our narrative is a fundamental part of our game, it relies on other disciplines.</p>
</div>


<h2 id="process" class="font-semibold text-xl mb-2 mt-4">Process</h2>
  <p>We developed our narrative based on a foundational premise, and loosely followed the steps below. All of our world building was created alongside our main story as supplemental material. 
<h3 id="premise" class="font-semibold mt-2">Premise:</h3>
  <p>A young kid, with an underwhelming skillset, dreams of one day becoming a Great Knight of his Kingdom. He finally receives an invitation to the Castle. However, when he arrives, the Knights have been locked in a room by a gang of misunderstood Wizards. It’s only through his unique mindset and skillset that he can break through to the Wizards and free the Knights.</p>
<h3 id="general" class="font-semibold mt-2">General Process:</h3>
  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside mb-2">
    <div class="italic">
    <li>Draft character profiles</li>
    <li>Identify overarching story beats</li>
    <li>Tie story beats to gameplay moments</li>
    </div>
    <li>Create character voices</li>
    <li>Draft dialogue</li>
    <li>Get dialogue approved by another team member</li>
    <li>Import and format in Engine [See <a class="text-purple-700 dark:text-purple-200" href="#bible">Narrative Bible</a> for information on Dialogue Manager]</li>
    <li>Script cutscenes</li>
  </ol>
<p>This outline looks quite linear, but our writing has a very iterative process. We would often return to character profiles or voices at later stages of production to update information. Steps 1-3 were generally less likely to change at later stages of production, but that wasn't a hard and fast rule. <span class="italic">We also esnured that all game writing had at least three rounds of writing and revisions.</span></p>

{# LESSON 2 #}
<div class="mb-4 rounded-lg p-2 mt-4 border border-purple-200 dark:border-purple-800 bg-purple-100 dark:bg-purple-900/20 rounded-lg">
  <h3 id="learned3" class="font-semibold">Lesson 3: Iterate</h3>
    <p class="ml-8">The more rewriting the narrative goes through, the better it will be. We intentionally allotted time so that we could go through multiple rounds of revisions!</p>
</div>


